## API Design Standards

### REST Endpoints

Use resource-based, lowercase, plural noun URLs.

```
GET    /api/v1/appointments              # List
GET    /api/v1/appointments/{id}         # Get by ID
POST   /api/v1/appointments              # Create
PUT    /api/v1/appointments/{id}         # Full update
PATCH  /api/v1/appointments/{id}         # Partial update
DELETE /api/v1/appointments/{id}         # Delete
```

### Request / Response Patterns

All responses return a consistent envelope:

```json
// Success
{
  "data": { ... },
  "message": "Operation completed"
}

// Paginated list
{
  "data": [ ... ],
  "meta": { "total": 42, "page": 1, "page_size": 20 }
}

// Error
{
  "error": "Human-readable message",
  "code": "SNAKE_CASE_CODE"
}
```

### HTTP Status Codes

| Scenario | Code |
|---|---|
| Created | 201 |
| No content (delete) | 204 |
| Validation error | 422 |
| Not found | 404 |
| Conflict | 409 |
| Unauthorized | 401 |
| Forbidden | 403 |
| Server error | 500 |

### Versioning

All routes are prefixed with `/api/v1`. New breaking versions introduce `/api/v2`.

### CORS

Configure CORS origins via environment variable `CORS_ORIGINS` (comma-separated). Always include both `http://localhost:<port>` and `http://*.local:<port>` for LAN dev access.

